00:17:38,724 --> 00:17:40,267
Well, this is it.

262
00:17:40,268 --> 00:17:43,228
The first time I've had
the old heave-ho, I must say.

263
00:17:43,229 --> 00:17:44,854
No, but you do understand?

264
00:17:44,855 --> 00:17:47,482
Frankly, I'm astonished
he put up with it for so long.

265
00:17:47,483 --> 00:17:49,985
Poor little devil.
You'll let us know where you are?

266
00:17:49,986 --> 00:17:51,528
Oh, sure.

267
00:17:51,529 --> 00:17:53,613
Were you happy here, Harry?

268
00:17:53,614 --> 00:17:55,323
The best billet I ever had.

269
00:17:55,324 --> 00:17:56,950
And you will write?

270
00:17:56,951 --> 00:17:58,577
Of course.

271
00:18:03,833 --> 00:18:06,001
Now, look, the cab's waiting.

272
00:18:06,002 --> 00:18:07,168
All right.

273
00:18:08,254 --> 00:18:09,629
(BELLE AND HARRY KISS)

274
00:18:09,630 --> 00:18:12,007
You won't think too badly of me,
will you?

275
00:18:12,008 --> 00:18:13,675
What a question.

276
00:18:13,676 --> 00:18:15,093
Now, look, I must go, really.

277
00:18:15,094 --> 00:18:17,470
Well, good luck.

278
00:18:17,471 --> 00:18:18,847
Bye-bye, Belle.

279
00:18:20,891 --> 00:18:23,518
(DOOR CLOSES)

280
00:18:26,272 --> 00:18:29,733
(PEOPLE CHATTER IN DISTANCE)

281
00:18:35,823 --> 00:18:37,157
Was that Mr Fawcett?

282
00:18:37,158 --> 00:18:38,408
Yes.

283
00:18:39,535 --> 00:18:40,952
I would've said goodbye to him.

284
00:18:40,953 --> 00:18:43,580
Well, he said to give you
his regards.

285
00:18:43,581 --> 00:18:45,915
Well, we'll have to find you
some other interests.

286
00:18:45,916 --> 00:18:47,542
Well, it's just that I get

287
00:18:47,543 --> 00:18:49,628
so lonely here all day by myself.

288
00:18:49,629 --> 00:18:52,589
You don't want to go on
the music halls again, do you?

289
00:18:52,590 --> 00:18:54,341
It's so tough in England.

290
00:18:54,342 --> 00:18:56,843
Besides, all the agents are crooked.

291
00:18:56,844 --> 00:19:00,305
Isn’t there some way you could
take up with show business again?

292
00:19:00,306 --> 00:19:01,598
You like the people,

293
00:19:01,682 --> 00:19:04,351
and it's your natural environment,
after all.

294
00:19:04,352 --> 00:19:06,561
Well, I suppose I could
join the guild or something.

295
00:19:06,562 --> 00:19:08,480
Clara's always asking me to.

296
00:19:08,481 --> 00:19:09,606
What guild is that?

297
00:19:09,607 --> 00:19:11,608
Well, the Ladies' Music Hall Guild.

298
00:19:11,609 --> 00:19:14,361
Looking after members
who've had a hard time.

299
00:19:14,362 --> 00:19:16,029
It's charitable work, really.

300
00:19:16,030 --> 00:19:17,322
They're all very fine women,

301
00:19:17,323 --> 00:19:19,783
and prominent in theatrical circles.

302
00:19:19,784 --> 00:19:21,993
It sounds much more your style.

303
00:19:22,078 --> 00:19:25,080
Of course, if I did want
to go on the stage again,

304
00:19:25,081 --> 00:19:27,207
they'd be able help me
get some decent dates.

305
00:19:27,208 --> 00:19:28,291
Exactly.

306
00:19:28,292 --> 00:19:30,585
I'll go and see Clara
this afternoon.

307
00:19:30,586 --> 00:19:35,173
You could have them meet here,
if you like.

308
00:19:35,174 --> 00:19:37,425
Oh, what a wonderful idea.

309
00:19:37,426 --> 00:19:40,637
Of course, I'd, uh...
I'd need a new dress and a hat.

310
00:19:40,638 --> 00:19:43,515
I saw a beautiful one
in Wight man’s the other day.

311
00:19:43,516 --> 00:19:45,975
It was orange taffeta
and it had puff sleeves

312
00:19:45,976 --> 00:19:47,686
and the neck right down to there.

313
00:19:47,770 --> 00:19:49,187
Why don't you buy it, then?

314
00:19:49,188 --> 00:19:51,731
I could get Mrs Thurman
to run me up something.

315
00:19:51,732 --> 00:19:53,775
Yes, blue perhaps?

316
00:19:53,776 --> 00:19:55,694
I saw a length of blue material
in the market

317
00:19:55,695 --> 00:19:57,737
that was going for a song.

318
00:19:57,738 --> 00:19:59,406
You get whatever you want.

319
00:19:59,407 --> 00:20:01,825
Oh, Peter, you are kind.

320
00:20:01,826 --> 00:20:02,909
(BRIGHT MUSIC)

321
00:20:02,910 --> 00:20:05,912
I know, I'll go up west and see
what they've got in the shops.

322
00:20:05,913 --> 00:20:07,539
Clara will know. What time is it?

323
00:20:07,623 --> 00:20:08,873
Almost 10 o'clock.

324
00:20:08,874 --> 00:20:10,500
Well, I'll have lunch
with Clara first,

325
00:20:10,501 --> 00:20:12,544
and we can arrange
about the meeting, too.

326
00:20:14,255 --> 00:20:15,964
(BRIGHT MUSIC)

327
00:20:15,965 --> 00:20:18,925
(KETTLE HISSES)

328
00:20:22,346 --> 00:20:23,888
The kettle's just boiling.

329
00:20:23,889 --> 00:20:25,598
I don't think they want any more.

330
00:20:25,599 --> 00:20:26,683
Are you sure?

331
00:20:26,684 --> 00:20:29,310
Well, the meeting went on so long,
they have to be getting home.

332
00:20:29,311 --> 00:20:30,770
Do you think it went well?

333
00:20:30,771 --> 00:20:32,230
They certainly liked you.

334
00:20:32,231 --> 00:20:34,607
Mrs Stratton's charming, isn't she?

335
00:20:34,608 --> 00:20:36,568
Well, she's the most important one,
really.

336
00:20:36,569 --> 00:20:38,069
She thinks you're lovely.

337
00:20:38,070 --> 00:20:40,113
If they don't want any more,
I’d better get back.

338
00:20:40,197 --> 00:20:42,615
-You don't have to go early, do you?
- Well, I can't be too late.

339
00:20:42,616 --> 00:20:44,284
Paul will be wanting his supper.

340
00:20:44,285 --> 00:20:45,869
I've something to tell you.

341
00:20:46,912 --> 00:20:49,456
- So we'll meet on Wednesday then?
- Yes, dear, delighted.

342
00:20:49,457 --> 00:20:51,374
I'll write Mr Ogilvie tomorrow

343
00:20:51,375 --> 00:20:53,334
and see if he can let us
have the material.

344
00:20:53,335 --> 00:20:56,045
I’m sure he will.
He's very interested in the guild.

345
00:20:56,046 --> 00:20:57,881
Must you really go so early?

346
00:20:57,882 --> 00:21:00,258
I'm afraid so, my dear.
It's nearly six already.

347
00:21:00,259 --> 00:21:01,760
Well, it was lovely of you to come,

348
00:21:01,761 --> 00:21:03,386
and thank you again for electing me.

349
00:21:03,387 --> 00:21:05,513
Not at all, it's our gain.

350
00:21:05,514 --> 00:21:08,308
It's so nice of you to let us meet
in your charming house.

351
00:21:08,392 --> 00:21:09,934
- Goodbye, Belle.
- Goodbye.

352
00:21:09,935 --> 00:21:11,936
- Goodbye, Mrs Crippen.
- Goodbye.

353
00:21:11,937 --> 00:21:13,146
- Goodbye.
- Goodbye.

354
00:21:13,147 --> 00:21:16,149
I shall look forward to seeing
much more of you in the future.

355
00:21:19,403 --> 00:21:21,446
Oh, it was wonderful!

356
00:21:21,447 --> 00:21:23,281
I told you.

357
00:21:23,282 --> 00:21:25,074
But they're so nice, all of them.

358
00:21:25,075 --> 00:21:27,911
Oh, they're all right. Of course,
we've all got something in common,

359
00:21:27,912 --> 00:21:29,996
being in the theatre,
and that's a help.

360
00:21:29,997 --> 00:21:32,582
What was it you wanted to tell me?

361
00:21:32,583 --> 00:21:34,542
What do you think of it?

362
00:21:34,543 --> 00:21:36,002
Lovely.

363
00:21:36,003 --> 00:21:38,213
I was admiring it
all through the meeting.

364
00:21:38,214 --> 00:21:40,590
Your husband
is really very generous.

365
00:21:40,674 --> 00:21:41,800
Peter?

366
00:21:41,801 --> 00:21:44,344
The only thing I get from him,
I have to wring out of him.

367
00:21:44,345 --> 00:21:45,762
This was a present.

368
00:21:45,763 --> 00:21:48,306
- From guess who?
- Oh, I’ve no idea.

369
00:21:49,475 --> 00:21:50,725
Not Bruce Martin?

370
00:21:50,726 --> 00:21:52,477
- (SHE GIGGLES)
- Yes!

371
00:21:52,478 --> 00:21:54,562
And he wrote me
the most wonderful letter.

372
00:21:54,563 --> 00:21:58,233
It begins,
"To my beautiful brown eyes."

373
00:21:58,234 --> 00:21:59,776
Here, now, read that bit.

374
00:22:08,035 --> 00:22:09,577
Well, what a thing
to say in a letter.

375
00:22:09,578 --> 00:22:11,996
He was always like that.
He just doesn't care.

376
00:22:11,997 --> 00:22:13,665
But what if Peter found it?

377
00:22:13,666 --> 00:22:16,876
It'd do him good to know
what normal men think of me.

378
00:22:16,877 --> 00:22:18,795
Oh, come on.

379
00:22:18,796 --> 00:22:21,589
Peter's a devoted husband.
Everyone says so.

380
00:22:21,590 --> 00:22:24,425
Yes, well, everyone
doesn't have to live with him.

381
00:22:24,426 --> 00:22:28,429
I'm a woman who needs something
a bit more practical and attention,

382
00:22:28,430 --> 00:22:30,557
if you get what I mean.

383
00:22:36,272 --> 00:22:38,690
But he must be mad
to write like this.

384
00:22:38,691 --> 00:22:40,358
Well, it's a special letter.

385
00:22:40,359 --> 00:22:41,985
The anniversary of the day we met.

386
00:22:41,986 --> 00:22:45,363
Now, you take my tip and burn it.

387
00:22:45,364 --> 00:22:47,991
It's far too dangerous
to leave lying about.

388
00:22:49,243 --> 00:22:51,244
Well, perhaps you're right.

389
00:22:53,497 --> 00:22:55,373
Bruce is what I call a man.

390
00:22:55,374 --> 00:22:57,625
If he walked
through that door right now,

391
00:22:57,626 --> 00:22:59,168
you wouldn't see me for dust.

392
00:22:59,169 --> 00:23:01,254
I thought it was all finished
years ago.

393
00:23:01,255 --> 00:23:03,256
Well, only because
he went back to Chicago,

394
00:23:03,257 --> 00:23:05,174
but it's possible
he might come back here,

395
00:23:05,175 --> 00:23:06,593
or we might go to the States.

396
00:23:06,594 --> 00:23:09,304
Oh, then what a celebration
there'd be.

397
00:23:09,305 --> 00:23:13,391
I tell you, Clara, no man ever
made me feel what old Brucie did.

398
00:23:13,392 --> 00:23:16,853
Oh, he's marvellous.

399
00:23:16,937 --> 00:23:19,439
(WHIMSICAL MUSIC)

400
00:23:22,067 --> 00:23:23,526
Mr Martin,

401
00:23:23,527 --> 00:23:26,529
did your relations with
Belle Elmore at any time

402
00:23:26,530 --> 00:23:28,823
come closer than mere friendship?

403
00:23:28,824 --> 00:23:30,742
Absolutely not.

404
00:23:30,743 --> 00:23:32,952
When did you last see her?

405
00:23:32,953 --> 00:23:37,665
About six years ago,
around April 1904.

406
00:23:37,666 --> 00:23:39,626
But you have communicated with her
since then?

407
00:23:39,627 --> 00:23:41,836
Yeah, we've exchanged letters.

408
00:23:41,837 --> 00:23:43,671
Frequently?

409
00:23:43,672 --> 00:23:46,132
Oh, she used to write to me about
three or four times a year.

410
00:23:46,216 --> 00:23:48,092
What kind of letters?

411
00:23:48,093 --> 00:23:50,053
Good wishes, you know,
that sort of thing.

412
00:23:51,305 --> 00:23:53,556
- Where do you live now?
- I beg your pardon?

413
00:23:54,642 --> 00:23:56,476
I said, where do you live now?

414
00:23:56,477 --> 00:23:59,896
Oh, I live in Chicago
with my wife and child.

415
00:23:59,897 --> 00:24:01,648
Was there ever a proposition

416
00:24:01,649 --> 00:24:04,359
that Belle Elmore
should come out to you?

417
00:24:04,360 --> 00:24:07,070
Absolutely not. No such thing.

418
00:24:07,071 --> 00:24:09,948
(MEN MUTTER)

419
00:24:14,161 --> 00:24:15,620
Mr Martin,

420
00:24:15,621 --> 00:24:17,789
as you have given up
the music hall stage,

421
00:24:17,790 --> 00:24:20,124
I take it you were a failure
in that profession?

422
00:24:20,125 --> 00:24:22,001
Absolutely not.

423
00:24:22,002 --> 00:24:24,087
I saw the opportunity of making
a bit more money.

424
00:24:24,088 --> 00:24:27,090
That's why I'm a real estate agent.
I wanted to support my family and...

425
00:24:27,091 --> 00:24:31,094
During Dr Crippen's absence
in America in 1899,

426
00:24:31,095 --> 00:24:32,845
how many times
did you see Mrs Crippen?

427
00:24:32,846 --> 00:24:35,181
I went to her house occasionally.

428
00:24:35,182 --> 00:24:37,558
How often is "occasionally"?

429
00:24:38,894 --> 00:24:39,978
Two or three times a week.

430
00:24:39,979 --> 00:24:42,271
At what hour of the day?

431
00:24:42,272 --> 00:24:43,564
Sometimes in the afternoons

432
00:24:43,565 --> 00:24:45,733
and sometimes in the evening.

433
00:24:45,734 --> 00:24:48,027
But always while Dr Crippen
was absent?

434
00:24:48,028 --> 00:24:49,195
Yes.

435
00:24:50,489 --> 00:24:52,573
Did you write often to Mrs Crippen?

436
00:24:52,574 --> 00:24:54,409
Well, not often.

437
00:24:54,410 --> 00:24:56,536
On what topics?

438
00:24:56,537 --> 00:24:57,870
Friendship.

439
00:24:57,871 --> 00:24:59,372
Were you in love with Mrs Crippen?

440
00:24:59,373 --> 00:25:00,498
Absolutely not.

441
00:25:01,709 --> 00:25:03,710
But you did tell her
that you loved her?

442
00:25:03,711 --> 00:25:06,796
Well, I wouldn't put it
exactly that way.

443
00:25:06,797 --> 00:25:08,756
Did you indicate that you loved her?

444
00:25:09,967 --> 00:25:12,176
Well, I suppose she
might've thought I did.

445
00:25:12,177 --> 00:25:13,845
You mean,
you deliberately misled her?

446
00:25:13,846 --> 00:25:15,972
Well, no,
I wouldn't put it exactly that way.

447
00:25:15,973 --> 00:25:18,057
She meant a great deal to me

448
00:25:18,058 --> 00:25:19,851
as far as friendship was concerned,

449
00:25:19,852 --> 00:25:22,186
but she was a married lady

450
00:25:22,187 --> 00:25:26,315
so it had to be
an entirely platonic friendship.

451
00:25:26,316 --> 00:25:28,860
(PEOPLE LAUGH)

452
00:25:30,821 --> 00:25:32,321
This is not a theatre.

453
00:25:32,322 --> 00:25:34,365
Members of the public
will control themselves

454
00:25:34,366 --> 00:25:35,908
or the court will be cleared.

455
00:25:37,828 --> 00:25:40,788
Mr Martin, kindly answer
this question directly.

456
00:25:41,832 --> 00:25:43,791
Were there any improper relations

457
00:25:43,792 --> 00:25:46,419
between you and Mrs Crippen
at any time?

458
00:25:46,420 --> 00:25:48,880
No, no, absolute not, My lord.

459
00:25:50,257 --> 00:25:52,592
Platonic or not,
did you ever show your esteem

460
00:25:52,593 --> 00:25:55,094
for Mrs Crippen
in any practical ways?

461
00:25:55,095 --> 00:25:57,889
Once in a while I gave her a little
present. Nothing extravagant.

462
00:25:57,890 --> 00:25:59,682
When was the last such gift?

463
00:25:59,683 --> 00:26:00,767
About a year ago.

464
00:26:00,768 --> 00:26:03,603
That would be two or three months
before her disappearance?

465
00:26:03,604 --> 00:26:05,021
Yes, I guess so.

466
00:26:05,022 --> 00:26:07,190
What was this gift?
Oh, a little brooch thing.

467
00:26:07,191 --> 00:26:09,025
An expensive one?

468
00:26:09,026 --> 00:26:11,527
Not very.
How much would it cost, then?

469
00:26:11,612 --> 00:26:14,572
Oh, about ten pounds in your money,
I guess.

470
00:26:15,866 --> 00:26:17,617
And you're telling us

471
00:26:17,618 --> 00:26:19,368
that five years after having had

472
00:26:19,369 --> 00:26:21,370
an entirely platonic friendship

473
00:26:21,371 --> 00:26:24,165
with a married woman whose husband
you had somehow never met,

474
00:26:24,166 --> 00:26:27,585
you sent her a gift
costing around ten pounds?

475
00:26:27,586 --> 00:26:29,879
Well, yes, I like to be
generous with my friends.

476
00:26:29,880 --> 00:26:32,048
Do you have many friends, Mr Martin?

477
00:26:32,049 --> 00:26:33,674
Oh, yes, lots.

478
00:26:33,675 --> 00:26:35,968
No wonder you needed to
take a more remunerative job

479
00:26:35,969 --> 00:26:38,304
than your talents could provide
from the theatre.

480
00:26:38,388 --> 00:26:40,848
(PEOPLE MUTTER)

481
00:26:42,184 --> 00:26:44,018
You may stand down.

482
00:26:44,019 --> 00:26:47,647
I wouldn't mind a bit of platonic
friendship with him myself!

483
00:26:47,648 --> 00:26:50,399
Call Dr David Pepper.

484
00:26:50,400 --> 00:26:52,401
Call Dr Pepper.

485
00:26:55,072 --> 00:26:58,032
Take the book in your right hand
and read the words on the card.

486
00:26:59,409 --> 00:27:00,910
"I swear by Almighty God

487
00:27:00,911 --> 00:27:04,080
"that the evidence I give
shall be the truth,

488
00:27:04,081 --> 00:27:06,874
"the whole truth
and nothing but the truth."

489
00:27:06,875 --> 00:27:10,837
Doctor, I believe you were
requested by the police

490
00:27:10,838 --> 00:27:13,673
to inspect some supposedly
human remains

491
00:27:13,674 --> 00:27:15,967
on a certain date, were you not?

492
00:27:15,968 --> 00:27:17,802
On July 14th this year,

493
00:27:17,803 --> 00:27:21,389
I went to 39 Hilldrop Crescent
with Chief Inspector Dew.

494
00:27:21,390 --> 00:27:23,224
In the cellar there,
I found that part

495
00:27:23,225 --> 00:27:24,934
of the floor had been taken up,

496
00:27:25,018 --> 00:27:28,146
and I saw what appeared to
be a mass of human remains.

497
00:27:28,147 --> 00:27:30,648
Ugh, this is the part I don't like.

498
00:27:30,649 --> 00:27:32,900
Do you want to leave then?
Are you mad?

499
00:27:32,901 --> 00:27:35,736
Just tell me when he's
finished with the gory details.

500
00:27:35,737 --> 00:27:38,197
..from the lower front
portion of the abdomen.

501
00:27:38,198 --> 00:27:40,741
There was a mark on it
which attracted my attention,

502
00:27:40,742 --> 00:27:42,869
and I afterwards examined
it with particularity.

503
00:27:42,870 --> 00:27:44,912
In your opinion, what was that mark?

504
00:27:44,913 --> 00:27:48,040
A scar, a little over
four inches in length.

505
00:27:48,041 --> 00:27:49,834
Having examined the remains,

506
00:27:49,918 --> 00:27:51,919
is it possible to say
whether the dissection

507
00:27:51,920 --> 00:27:55,006
was done by a skilled person or not?

508
00:27:55,007 --> 00:27:57,842
Definitely by a skilled person.

509
00:27:57,843 --> 00:28:00,011
Would the position of the scar
suggest to you

510
00:28:00,012 --> 00:28:01,554
a particular type of operation?

511
00:28:01,555 --> 00:28:03,931
Yes, it would correspond

512
00:28:03,932 --> 00:28:06,142
to an operation in a female person,

513
00:28:06,143 --> 00:28:08,144
for the removal of certain organs.

514
00:28:08,145 --> 00:28:11,063
Did you form an opinion
as to the cause of death?

515
00:28:11,064 --> 00:28:14,442
Yes, by treating the organs
with the usual process,

516
00:28:14,526 --> 00:28:17,278
I found a mydriatic alkaloid
presence.

517
00:28:17,279 --> 00:28:18,529
On further tests,

518
00:28:18,530 --> 00:28:20,156
I found that it corresponded

519
00:28:20,157 --> 00:28:22,033
to hyoscine hydrobromide.

520
00:28:22,034 --> 00:28:25,036
What are the properties
of hyoscine, Doctor?

521
00:28:25,037 --> 00:28:26,787
It is a powerful narcotic, My Lord.

522
00:28:26,788 --> 00:28:29,874
Have you any knowledge of its
medical use?

523
00:28:29,875 --> 00:28:32,293
I have heard
that it is sometimes used

524
00:28:32,294 --> 00:28:35,463
for pacifying
extreme nervous disorders

525
00:28:35,464 --> 00:28:37,381
in certain American hospitals.

526
00:28:37,466 --> 00:28:41,052
What is the fatal dose of hyoscine,
Doctor?

527
00:28:41,053 --> 00:28:43,804
Between a quarter and half a grain.

528
00:28:43,805 --> 00:28:47,183
And what amount of hyoscine
did you find in the remains?

529
00:28:47,184 --> 00:28:49,227
From the amount in the organs,

530
00:28:49,228 --> 00:28:50,853
there would certainly have been more

531
00:28:50,854 --> 00:28:52,521
than halfa grain
in the entire body.

532
00:28:52,522 --> 00:28:55,274
Doctor, just tell us what effect

533
00:28:55,275 --> 00:28:57,276
a fatal dose would have
on a human being.

534
00:28:57,277 --> 00:29:01,280
It would perhaps produce
delirium and excitement at first,

535
00:29:01,281 --> 00:29:03,157
and then the patient
would become drowsy,

536
00:29:03,242 --> 00:29:05,993
and probably die after a few hours.

537
00:29:05,994 --> 00:29:08,537
Does hyoscine
have a distinguishing taste?

538
00:29:08,538 --> 00:29:10,331
It is rather salt and bitter,

539
00:29:10,332 --> 00:29:13,167
but it can be administered in
something with a pronounced flavour.

540
00:29:13,168 --> 00:29:15,419
Like, um, stout beer,

541
00:29:15,420 --> 00:29:17,964
sweetened tea or coffee.

542
00:29:17,965 --> 00:29:19,674
No more questions.

543
00:29:19,675 --> 00:29:21,634
Taking the remains as a whole,

544
00:29:21,635 --> 00:29:23,427
it was impossible
to determine the sex.

545
00:29:23,428 --> 00:29:24,595
That is correct.

546
00:29:24,680 --> 00:29:27,890
As to the mark you claim
was a scar from the abdomen,

547
00:29:27,891 --> 00:29:30,935
what operation in a male person
would cause it in that position?

548
00:29:30,936 --> 00:29:33,771
The removal of stones
from the bladder, for one thing.

549
00:29:33,772 --> 00:29:36,357
Before you formed the opinion
that the mark was a scar,

550
00:29:36,358 --> 00:29:39,443
you had already learned that
Mrs Crippen had an operation.

551
00:29:39,444 --> 00:29:40,653
Certainly.

552
00:29:40,654 --> 00:29:42,363
On July 15th,

553
00:29:42,364 --> 00:29:44,824
did not you and Dr Marshall
at the mortuary

554
00:29:44,825 --> 00:29:47,994
examine the remains
together for some hours?

555
00:29:47,995 --> 00:29:49,829
- We did.
- On that occasion,

556
00:29:49,913 --> 00:29:51,956
you did not come to the opinion
that it was a scar.

557
00:29:51,957 --> 00:29:54,542
I did not see the mark at all
on that occasion.

558
00:29:54,543 --> 00:29:57,295
Was it not three days later,
about July 18th,

559
00:29:57,296 --> 00:30:00,006
that you learned first
from the newspapers

560
00:30:00,007 --> 00:30:01,799
that Mrs Crippen
had a scar on her abdomen?

561
00:30:01,800 --> 00:30:03,592
I cannot remember
when I first heard it.

562
00:30:03,593 --> 00:30:07,388
But it was certainly after your
first examination on July 15th?

563
00:30:07,389 --> 00:30:08,639
Oh, yes.

564
00:30:08,640 --> 00:30:10,016
That'll be all.

565
00:30:10,017 --> 00:30:12,768
(PEOPLE MUTTER)

566
00:30:12,853 --> 00:30:14,312
Call Emily Jackson.

567
00:30:14,313 --> 00:30:15,938
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

568
00:30:15,939 --> 00:30:18,065
Call Emily Jackson.

569
00:30:21,820 --> 00:30:24,739
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

570
00:30:33,582 --> 00:30:37,168
Take the book in your right hand
and read the words on the card.

571
00:30:37,169 --> 00:30:39,545
"I swear by Almighty God..."

572
00:30:39,546 --> 00:30:40,838
How friendly is she?

573
00:30:40,839 --> 00:30:43,341
She's very devoted to the girl,
but she's so confused.

574
00:30:43,342 --> 00:30:44,842
He may make her say anything.

575
00:30:44,843 --> 00:30:46,010
Hmm.

576
00:30:46,011 --> 00:30:48,054
Now, Mrs Jackson,

577
00:30:48,055 --> 00:30:51,349
Miss Le Neve lived in your house
for some time, did she not?

578
00:30:51,350 --> 00:30:54,060
I was her landlady
for nearly two years.

579
00:30:54,061 --> 00:30:56,437
What were the relations between you?

580
00:30:56,521 --> 00:30:58,230
We were on quite different terms

581
00:30:58,231 --> 00:31:00,107
to the ordinary landlady and lodger.

582
00:31:00,108 --> 00:31:01,734
From your experience of her,

583
00:31:01,735 --> 00:31:04,779
did you notice any change
in her manner

584
00:31:04,780 --> 00:31:10,201
at the end of January
or the beginning of February 1910?

585
00:31:10,202 --> 00:31:11,869
Yes.

586
00:31:11,870 --> 00:31:16,082
One day, she came home looking
very tired and strange.

587
00:31:16,083 --> 00:31:19,210
Did she display other symptoms
of disquiet?

588
00:31:20,462 --> 00:31:22,171
She was greatly agitated.

589
00:31:22,172 --> 00:31:24,465
How did this manifest itself?

590
00:31:24,466 --> 00:31:26,592
Her whole body was trembling.

591
00:31:26,593 --> 00:31:29,512
She looked as though
she'd had some kind of a shock.

592
00:31:29,513 --> 00:31:31,889
Did she give any explanation

593
00:31:31,890 --> 00:31:33,474
for her appearance?

594
00:31:33,475 --> 00:31:35,393
She went straight up to bed.

595
00:31:35,394 --> 00:31:38,312
Later on, I sat up with her
until two o'clock in the morning.

596
00:31:38,313 --> 00:31:41,148
Did she subsequently explain to you

597
00:31:41,149 --> 00:31:42,441
the cause of the shock?

598
00:31:42,526 --> 00:31:46,153
She was too ill
to go to work the next day.

599
00:31:46,154 --> 00:31:49,782
I told her, if she didn't tell me
what was troubling her,

600
00:31:49,783 --> 00:31:51,492
she'd go out of her mind.

601
00:31:51,493 --> 00:31:53,953
What was her reply?

602
00:31:55,247 --> 00:31:57,665
She said it was too dreadful
to talk about.

603
00:31:57,666 --> 00:31:59,041
(CROWD MUTTER)

604
00:31:59,042 --> 00:32:01,460
"Too dreadful to talk about."

605
00:32:03,130 --> 00:32:05,297
Did she later embroider
on that explanation?

606
00:32:05,298 --> 00:32:06,799
No.

607
00:32:08,301 --> 00:32:12,096
Now, up until this time, she'd been
living at home with you continually.

608
00:32:12,097 --> 00:32:13,305
Yes.

609
00:32:13,306 --> 00:32:15,724
Did she remain so?
No.

610
00:32:15,725 --> 00:32:18,936
Then she started
staying away nights.

611
00:32:18,937 --> 00:32:21,147
And when she came back to see you,

612
00:32:21,148 --> 00:32:22,940
what was her manner?

613
00:32:25,235 --> 00:32:26,527
She was radiant.

614
00:32:28,572 --> 00:32:30,030
Was she alone?

615
00:32:30,031 --> 00:32:32,950
No. Dr Crippen was with her.

616
00:32:32,951 --> 00:32:35,327
Did she bring you anything?

617
00:32:35,328 --> 00:32:36,787
Yes.

618
00:32:36,788 --> 00:32:40,708
She brought a number of articles
of women's clothing.

619
00:32:40,709 --> 00:32:43,043
Did she explain where this
clothing had come from?

620
00:32:43,044 --> 00:32:44,962
Yes.

621
00:32:46,339 --> 00:32:50,092
She said it had belonged
to Mrs Crippen, who had gone away.

622
00:32:50,093 --> 00:32:52,845
(CROWD MUTTER)

623
00:32:57,100 --> 00:32:58,601
Mrs Jackson,

624
00:32:58,602 --> 00:33:00,394
how did Miss Le Neve address you?

625
00:33:01,730 --> 00:33:03,772
She called me "Mother".

626
00:33:03,773 --> 00:33:06,275
Would you say you had a good memory,
Mrs Jackson?

627
00:33:06,276 --> 00:33:08,152
Not bad.

628
00:33:08,153 --> 00:33:10,488
I'm forgetful about some things.

629
00:33:10,489 --> 00:33:11,697
Such as dates?

630
00:33:11,698 --> 00:33:16,076
Well, I don't pay much
attention to time normally.

631
00:33:16,077 --> 00:33:18,913
So, when you mention a time
or a date,

632
00:33:18,914 --> 00:33:21,040
it's largely guesswork?

633
00:33:21,041 --> 00:33:22,249
I'm afraid so.

634
00:33:22,250 --> 00:33:24,960
But when the police
interviewed you in July,

635
00:33:25,045 --> 00:33:26,462
six months later than the event

636
00:33:26,463 --> 00:33:28,339
you've just described
to my learned friend,

637
00:33:28,340 --> 00:33:31,425
you naturally tried
to fix the date for them?

638
00:33:31,426 --> 00:33:35,179
Yes, they were most insistent
about that particular date.

639
00:33:35,180 --> 00:33:36,931
You already knew from the newspaper

640
00:33:36,932 --> 00:33:39,016
that Belle Elmore, Mrs Crippen,

641
00:33:39,017 --> 00:33:41,519
had not been seen since
February 1st?

642
00:33:41,520 --> 00:33:42,937
Yes, I'd read that.

643
00:33:42,938 --> 00:33:44,146
Will you tell us,

644
00:33:44,147 --> 00:33:47,316
was the strangeness and shock
you mentioned

645
00:33:47,400 --> 00:33:49,485
confined to the end of January only?

646
00:33:49,486 --> 00:33:52,738
No, she started behaving oddly

647
00:33:52,739 --> 00:33:54,323
at the beginning of the month,

648
00:33:54,324 --> 00:33:55,908
just after the new year.

649
00:33:55,909 --> 00:33:58,577
So we may take it that
for the whole of January,

650
00:33:58,578 --> 00:34:00,621
she was miserable and depressed?

651
00:34:00,622 --> 00:34:01,789
Yes.

652
00:34:01,790 --> 00:34:03,165
Subsequent of the conversation

653
00:34:03,166 --> 00:34:05,125
you have described
to my learned friend,

654
00:34:05,126 --> 00:34:07,920
did you discover
what was really troubling her?

655
00:34:08,004 --> 00:34:12,049
Well, she was upset because someone
in the office didn't like her,

656
00:34:12,050 --> 00:34:15,636
and she was afraid they would
turn Dr Crippen against her.

657
00:34:15,637 --> 00:34:17,513
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

658
00:34:17,514 --> 00:34:18,764
Thank you.

659
00:34:18,765 --> 00:34:20,057
That will be all.

660
00:34:21,560 --> 00:34:24,436
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

661
00:34:35,574 --> 00:34:38,325
(BRIGHT MUSIC)

662
00:34:43,081 --> 00:34:46,166
Well, I can't make head nor tail
of the doctor's writing again.

663
00:34:46,167 --> 00:34:47,751
Now, what is that?

664
00:34:49,838 --> 00:34:51,922
"Repeat nerve tonic number four."

665
00:34:51,923 --> 00:34:54,008
It could've been Chinese,
as far as I'm concerned.

666
00:34:54,009 --> 00:34:55,134
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

667
00:34:59,723 --> 00:35:01,890
- Morning, Miss Curnow.
- Morning, Doctor.

668
00:35:03,685 --> 00:35:05,311
Dr Crippen not in yet?

669
00:35:09,316 --> 00:35:11,400
He's calling at the chemist
on the way in.

670
00:35:11,401 --> 00:35:13,736
I'd be obliged
if you'd type these up for me?

671
00:35:13,737 --> 00:35:14,862
Of course.

672
00:35:16,698 --> 00:35:18,115
When could they be ready?

673
00:35:19,242 --> 00:35:20,409
By lunchtime.

674
00:35:21,202 --> 00:35:22,328
Unless you're in a rush.

675
00:35:22,329 --> 00:35:24,913
No, that'll be all right.

676
00:35:37,719 --> 00:35:40,804
Well, you've certainly
got what it takes.

677
00:35:40,805 --> 00:35:42,264
What do you mean?

678
00:35:42,265 --> 00:35:43,807
The way Dr Rogers
was looking at you,

679
00:35:43,808 --> 00:35:46,935
I thought he was gonna jump down
inside that blouse.

680
00:35:46,936 --> 00:35:48,020
It's nice, isn't it?

681
00:35:48,021 --> 00:35:49,647
-A present?
- Mmm.

682
00:35:51,691 --> 00:35:54,360
Dr Crippen is very generous.
You must give him that.

683
00:35:55,695 --> 00:35:58,364
Come on, you don't think
it's a secret, do you?

684
00:36:00,367 --> 00:36:02,910
I honestly don't know
what you're talking about.

685
00:36:02,911 --> 00:36:04,286
Oh, no?

686
00:36:20,845 --> 00:36:22,471
Good morning.

687
00:36:24,182 --> 00:36:25,724
Good morning.

688
00:36:38,446 --> 00:36:40,239
Anything in the mail?

689
00:36:40,240 --> 00:36:42,658
Mostly glowing testimonials
from old ladies

690
00:36:42,659 --> 00:36:45,911
who've recovered from sciatica
after using one of your remedies.

691
00:36:45,912 --> 00:36:47,121
Good.

692
00:36:48,415 --> 00:36:49,832
Any orders?

693
00:36:49,833 --> 00:36:51,667
Three.

694
00:36:51,668 --> 00:36:53,127
Only three?

695
00:36:58,341 --> 00:37:00,467
Have you come into money?

696
00:37:00,468 --> 00:37:01,719
No, why?

697
00:37:01,720 --> 00:37:04,555
You have an air
of secret satisfaction.

698
00:37:04,556 --> 00:37:07,099
It’s just that a girl
likes to be admired.

699
00:37:08,351 --> 00:37:09,518
Mm-hmm.

700
00:37:11,688 --> 00:37:13,397
You mean, I have a rival?

701
00:37:16,526 --> 00:37:17,985
Who is it?

702
00:37:17,986 --> 00:37:19,403
Just a man.

703
00:37:19,404 --> 00:37:20,904
Someone you know.

704
00:37:22,031 --> 00:37:24,241
Not... Rogers?

705
00:37:24,242 --> 00:37:27,703
Yes. He came into the office
to give me some letters,

706
00:37:27,704 --> 00:37:29,371
and couldn't take his eyes off me.

707
00:37:29,372 --> 00:37:31,290
Miss Curnow thinks
he's getting sweet on me.

708
00:37:31,291 --> 00:37:33,375
Well...

709
00:37:33,376 --> 00:37:37,463
perhaps I’d better leave the field
free for a younger man.

710
00:37:37,464 --> 00:37:38,630
He's not younger.

711
00:37:38,631 --> 00:37:40,048
He's 46, I'm 48.

712
00:37:40,049 --> 00:37:42,885
Well, I don't care. He looks at
least ten years older than you.

713
00:37:44,053 --> 00:37:45,804
Aren't you jealous, though?

714
00:37:47,640 --> 00:37:48,766
Raging with it.

715
00:37:54,689 --> 00:37:55,814
Hawley.

716
00:37:56,858 --> 00:37:58,192
Hmm?

717
00:37:59,611 --> 00:38:01,320
When can we see each other?

718
00:38:03,406 --> 00:38:04,531
Tomorrow...

719
00:38:06,117 --> 00:38:07,576
..if you like.

720
00:38:07,577 --> 00:38:08,952
Tomorrow?

721
00:38:10,205 --> 00:38:11,371
Oh, yes.

722
00:38:11,372 --> 00:38:12,873
(DOOR CREAKS)

723
00:38:14,042 --> 00:38:16,168
(GENTLE MUSIC)

724
00:38:31,851 --> 00:38:33,685
(DOOR THUDS IN DISTANCE)

725
00:38:38,691 --> 00:38:41,777
(KEYS CLACK ON TYPEWRITER)

726
00:38:50,912 --> 00:38:54,623
(BELL TOLLS IN DISTANCE)

727
00:38:59,170 --> 00:39:00,337
All right?

728
00:39:02,340 --> 00:39:03,841
Wonderful.

729
00:39:05,426 --> 00:39:08,053
Are you sure
you don't want me to stay?

730
00:39:08,054 --> 00:39:11,223
Better not, it's after six already.

731
00:39:11,224 --> 00:39:13,559
I don't see why I can't stay
if I want to.

732
00:39:13,560 --> 00:39:16,228
Well, we don't want people talking.

733
00:39:17,355 --> 00:39:20,232
People. I hate people.

734
00:39:21,276 --> 00:39:23,068
Goodnight then, Doctor.

735
00:39:23,069 --> 00:39:25,279
Goodnight.

736
00:39:25,280 --> 00:39:26,947
Goodnight, Dr Rogers.

737
00:39:26,948 --> 00:39:28,365
Goodnight.

738
00:39:29,993 --> 00:39:32,369
I'm not disturbing you?

739
00:39:32,370 --> 00:39:33,912
No, of course not.

740
00:39:33,913 --> 00:39:36,206
It's rather a delicate matter,
really.

741
00:39:36,207 --> 00:39:38,750
I'd be grateful if you'd have
a word with your typist

742
00:39:38,751 --> 00:39:41,211
about her, um, costume.

743
00:39:42,505 --> 00:39:43,797
In what way?

744
00:39:43,798 --> 00:39:47,885
She has a tendency to look
a bit flash for an office.

745
00:39:47,886 --> 00:39:50,470
Low-cut fronts,
too much jewellery, you know.

746
00:39:51,639 --> 00:39:53,557
I'm afraid I hadn't noticed.

747
00:39:53,558 --> 00:39:55,767
It's become markedly worse lately.

748
00:39:55,768 --> 00:39:57,227
I've heard several comments.

749
00:39:57,228 --> 00:39:58,604
I'm sorry.

750
00:39:58,605 --> 00:40:00,856
Just have a word with her,
will you, Doctor?

751
00:40:00,857 --> 00:40:02,524
We don't want any scandal.

752
00:40:02,525 --> 00:40:04,192
You know what people are.

753
00:40:04,193 --> 00:40:07,529
Yes, of course, I'll talk to
her about it in the morning.

754
00:40:07,530 --> 00:40:09,406
Splendid.

755
00:40:09,407 --> 00:40:10,741
Splendid.

756
00:40:14,913 --> 00:40:18,457
(GENTLE MUSIC PLAYS ON PHONOGRAPH)

757
00:40:18,458 --> 00:40:20,542
I hate this sordid hotel.

758
00:40:21,794 --> 00:40:22,836
I love it.

759
00:40:24,255 --> 00:40:27,758
It's the only place that
we're ever really alone.

760
00:40:30,345 --> 00:40:31,929
(HE GROANS)

761
00:40:31,930 --> 00:40:33,513
Here, let me help you.

762
00:40:33,514 --> 00:40:35,098
Come into the light.

763
00:40:35,099 --> 00:40:36,475
I haven't got my glasses.

764
00:40:38,770 --> 00:40:41,730
(CARRIAGES RATTLING IN DISTANCE)

765
00:40:42,899 --> 00:40:44,066
There.

766
00:40:54,702 --> 00:40:55,869
I love you..

767
00:40:57,163 --> 00:40:58,747
..Ethel Le Neve.

768
00:40:59,832 --> 00:41:01,249
I love you too, Hawley.

769
00:41:04,128 --> 00:41:05,212
Hawley.

770
00:41:06,339 --> 00:41:08,465
No, I must go.

771
00:41:08,466 --> 00:41:11,259
I don't want to, but I must.

772
00:41:11,260 --> 00:41:13,136
Can't you tell her
you were working late?

773
00:41:13,137 --> 00:41:18,183
I hate involving you
in lies and deceit.

774
00:41:18,184 --> 00:41:19,893
I don't care, Hawley.

775
00:41:21,145 --> 00:41:23,772
I don't care about
where we meet or how often.

776
00:41:25,316 --> 00:41:27,359
Just as long as I can
go on seeing you

777
00:41:27,360 --> 00:41:28,777
every day at the office.

778
00:41:30,196 --> 00:41:32,781
And having these times together
