(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC)

1138
01:00:55,777 --> 01:00:57,194
Was there a quarrel of any sort

1139
01:00:57,195 --> 01:01:00,114
that you saw or heard
during that evening?

1140
01:01:00,115 --> 01:01:02,867
Not that I saw, no.

1141
01:01:02,868 --> 01:01:04,827
Did Mrs Crippen seem in good health?

1142
01:01:04,828 --> 01:01:08,164
Oh, yes,
she was quite her usual self.

1143
01:01:08,165 --> 01:01:09,582
Full of good humour, you mean?

1144
01:01:09,583 --> 01:01:11,292
Quite remarkably so.

1145
01:01:11,293 --> 01:01:13,002
Did she seem fond of Dr Crippen?

1146
01:01:13,003 --> 01:01:14,753
Devoted.

1147
01:01:14,754 --> 01:01:18,549
She was a very good and loyal wife.

1148
01:01:18,633 --> 01:01:20,885
What time did you leave
that evening?

1149
01:01:20,886 --> 01:01:22,011
About half-past one.

1150
01:01:22,012 --> 01:01:25,222
Did you see Mrs Crippen again?

1151
01:01:25,223 --> 01:01:26,348
No.

1152
01:01:26,349 --> 01:01:29,310
But later, Dr Crippen told you
something about her?

1153
01:01:29,311 --> 01:01:32,354
He said that Belle had suddenly
been called to America,

1154
01:01:32,355 --> 01:01:34,690
to visit a sick relative.

1155
01:01:34,691 --> 01:01:36,609
And this surprised you?

1156
01:01:36,610 --> 01:01:37,526
Very much so.

1157
01:01:37,527 --> 01:01:41,864
Now, do you recall anything
that he told you on March 23rd?

1158
01:01:41,948 --> 01:01:45,451
That was the Wednesday
before Easter.

1159
01:01:45,452 --> 01:01:48,704
Yes, he said that he'd
had a cable from Belle.

1160
01:01:48,705 --> 01:01:50,372
She'd been taken dangerously ill.

1161
01:01:50,373 --> 01:01:53,334
He expected to hear any moment
that she'd gone.

1162
01:01:53,335 --> 01:01:56,837
Did you hear from him
subsequent to that?

1163
01:01:56,838 --> 01:01:59,298
Yes, I had a telegram
the next morning,

1164
01:01:59,299 --> 01:02:04,553
saying, "Belle died yesterday
at six o'clock, Peter."

1165
01:02:04,554 --> 01:02:07,264
Peter. That was the name
by which you knew him?

1166
01:02:07,265 --> 01:02:08,224
Yes.

1167
01:02:08,225 --> 01:02:13,520
Now, I want to ask you
about an occasion in 1908,

1168
01:02:13,605 --> 01:02:15,356
when you were in
Mrs Crippen's bedroom

1169
01:02:15,357 --> 01:02:16,774
while she was undressing.

1170
01:02:17,859 --> 01:02:21,237
Did you see anything
remarkable in her appearance?

1171
01:02:21,238 --> 01:02:22,446
Yes.

1172
01:02:22,447 --> 01:02:26,742
She...
She was naked under her housecoat,

1173
01:02:26,743 --> 01:02:30,329
and when it fell open,
I saw that she had a scar.

1174
01:02:30,330 --> 01:02:31,413
Here.

1175
01:02:32,874 --> 01:02:33,791
Did you speak about it?

1176
01:02:33,792 --> 01:02:35,918
Yes.

1177
01:02:35,919 --> 01:02:38,545
I said, "Belle, does that hurt?"

1178
01:02:38,546 --> 01:02:41,340
But she just smiled
and said it didn't.

1179
01:02:41,341 --> 01:02:42,758
Now, Mrs Arditti,

1180
01:02:42,759 --> 01:02:45,010
I ask you to cast your mind back

1181
01:02:45,011 --> 01:02:47,554
to the evening of February 20th
this year.

1182
01:02:47,555 --> 01:02:51,183
Did anything of interest
occur on that date?

1183
01:02:51,184 --> 01:02:54,270
Oh, yes, we had our annual ball,

1184
01:02:54,271 --> 01:02:55,896
for the Guild Benevolent Fund.

1185
01:02:55,981 --> 01:02:58,107
Was Dr Crippen there?

1186
01:02:58,108 --> 01:03:00,776
Yes, with Miss Le Neve.

1187
01:03:02,070 --> 01:03:03,362
Was any comment made about them?

1188
01:03:03,363 --> 01:03:04,822
A lady came up,

1189
01:03:04,823 --> 01:03:06,782
and after she'd spoken to me,

1190
01:03:06,783 --> 01:03:08,284
I looked at Miss Le Neve,

1191
01:03:08,285 --> 01:03:11,537
and saw that
she was wearing a brooch.

1192
01:03:11,538 --> 01:03:15,499
Did it remind you of one
that you'd seen someone else wear?

1193
01:03:15,500 --> 01:03:19,795
Well, it was very like
one worn by Mrs Crippen.

1194
01:03:21,298 --> 01:03:23,674
Did Mrs Crippen also wear furs?

1195
01:03:23,675 --> 01:03:26,302
She had two sets of furs.

1196
01:03:26,303 --> 01:03:29,096
After Mrs Crippen's disappearance,

1197
01:03:29,097 --> 01:03:33,350
did you see anyone else
wearing a set like hers?

1198
01:03:33,351 --> 01:03:36,186
Yes, Miss Le Neve.

1199
01:03:39,941 --> 01:03:41,233
No more questions, M'lud.

1200
01:03:45,655 --> 01:03:48,198
How long did you know
Dr and Mrs Crippen?

1201
01:03:48,199 --> 01:03:50,284
About 18 months.

1202
01:03:50,285 --> 01:03:53,329
Would you say that Dr Crippen
was a kind-hearted man,

1203
01:03:53,330 --> 01:03:54,580
so far as you could see?

1204
01:03:54,581 --> 01:03:57,082
So far as I could see, yes.

1205
01:03:58,001 --> 01:04:00,961
Now, taking the dinner party
on Monday, January 31st,

1206
01:04:00,962 --> 01:04:03,339
it was a happy party, as you said,
a pleasant party?

1207
01:04:03,340 --> 01:04:04,256
Perfectly.

1208
01:04:04,257 --> 01:04:06,300
You did not notice anything unusual

1209
01:04:06,301 --> 01:04:08,844
in Dr Crippen's manner
on that evening?

1210
01:04:08,845 --> 01:04:10,763
- Not really.
- Did you or didn't you?

1211
01:04:12,307 --> 01:04:13,599
No.

1212
01:04:13,600 --> 01:04:14,850
He was happy, talking,

1213
01:04:14,851 --> 01:04:16,518
and all that kind of thing?

1214
01:04:16,519 --> 01:04:20,481
Well, he had a slight difference

1215
01:04:20,482 --> 01:04:22,232
with Mrs Crippen about something.

1216
01:04:23,693 --> 01:04:25,861
But apart from that,
he was his usual self.

1217
01:04:25,862 --> 01:04:27,738
What caused this difference?

1218
01:04:28,573 --> 01:04:31,950
Belle thought he should've
escorted my husband upstairs.

1219
01:04:31,951 --> 01:04:34,620
What was Dr Crippen's
reaction to that?

1220
01:04:34,621 --> 01:04:36,080
He didn't say very much at all.

1221
01:04:36,081 --> 01:04:38,123
It didn't provoke him to anger?

1222
01:04:38,124 --> 01:04:42,336
No, he was always very calm
and controlled.

1223
01:04:43,713 --> 01:04:45,672
Now, taking the ball
on February 20th,

1224
01:04:45,673 --> 01:04:47,508
you rather pressed him
to attend, did you not?

1225
01:04:47,509 --> 01:04:50,094
I asked him if he wanted to go.

1226
01:04:50,095 --> 01:04:52,304
And I told him the tickets
were halfa guinea each.

1227
01:04:52,305 --> 01:04:54,556
That was a place where he knew
if he took Miss Le Neve,

1228
01:04:54,557 --> 01:04:57,684
they would meet a great many
of Mrs Crippen's friends.

1229
01:04:57,685 --> 01:04:58,602
I suppose so.

1230
01:04:58,603 --> 01:05:00,521
And that piece of jewellery
you mentioned

1231
01:05:00,522 --> 01:05:02,648
was worn quite openly
on the bodice of her dress?

1232
01:05:02,649 --> 01:05:03,524
Yes.

1233
01:05:03,608 --> 01:05:06,527
He did not seem in anyway uneasy in
the presence of his wife's friends?

1234
01:05:06,528 --> 01:05:08,445
Quite the reverse.

1235
01:05:08,446 --> 01:05:10,447
He seemed very proud
of Miss Le Neve.

1236
01:05:10,448 --> 01:05:12,574
Showing her off.

1237
01:05:14,160 --> 01:05:16,245
Just a moment, Chief Inspector.

1238
01:05:16,246 --> 01:05:18,288
You say Mrs Arditti came to see you

1239
01:05:18,289 --> 01:05:20,290
at Scotland Yard on the 30th June?

1240
01:05:20,291 --> 01:05:21,166
Yes, My Lord.

1241
01:05:21,167 --> 01:05:23,627
This was the first time
you'd heard of the Crippens?

1242
01:05:23,628 --> 01:05:24,545
Yes, My Lord.

1243
01:05:24,546 --> 01:05:29,258
Did Mrs Arditti explain
why she had come to see you?

1244
01:05:29,259 --> 01:05:32,386
She made a statement, in consequence
of which I made enquiries,

1245
01:05:32,387 --> 01:05:34,805
between that date and the 8th July,

1246
01:05:34,806 --> 01:05:36,890
with reference to
the disappearance of Mrs Crippen.

1247
01:05:36,975 --> 01:05:40,185
And on July 8th, did you
visit a certain address?

1248
01:05:40,186 --> 01:05:43,856
I went with Sergeant Mitchell

1249
01:05:43,857 --> 01:05:46,358
to number 39 Hilldrop Crescent,

1250
01:05:46,359 --> 01:05:48,694
where I saw Miss Le Neve.

1251
01:05:48,695 --> 01:05:50,028
I had a conversation with her,

1252
01:05:50,029 --> 01:05:51,655
and then went with her
to Albion House,

1253
01:05:51,656 --> 01:05:53,740
where I saw the prisoner, Crippen.

1254
01:05:53,741 --> 01:05:56,618
Later that day, toward evening,

1255
01:05:56,619 --> 01:05:58,579
I went with Crippen and Miss Le Neve

1256
01:05:58,580 --> 01:06:00,247
back to number 39 Hilldrop Crescent.

1257
01:06:00,331 --> 01:06:03,000
Did you have an opportunity
of examining the house?

1258
01:06:03,001 --> 01:06:06,712
Yes, he showed me into every room,

1259
01:06:06,713 --> 01:06:08,380
and also round the garden.

1260
01:06:09,674 --> 01:06:12,092
I said to him,

1261
01:06:12,093 --> 01:06:14,052
"Of course, we shall have to find

1262
01:06:14,053 --> 01:06:15,721
"Mrs Crippen
to clear this matter up."

1263
01:06:16,848 --> 01:06:20,809
And he said,
"Yes, I will do everything I can.

1264
01:06:20,810 --> 01:06:23,479
"Would an advertisement
be any good?"

1265
01:06:24,898 --> 01:06:27,357
Together,
we composed an advertisement

1266
01:06:27,358 --> 01:06:28,692
in Crippen's handwriting,

1267
01:06:28,693 --> 01:06:32,488
asking for information
about his wife, Belle Elmore.

1268
01:06:32,489 --> 01:06:34,406
What was done with that
advertisement?

1269
01:06:35,575 --> 01:06:37,910
It remained with Crippen that night

1270
01:06:37,911 --> 01:06:41,079
when Sergeant Mitchell
and I left the house.

1271
01:06:41,748 --> 01:06:45,000
I'll send it to the American
papers tomorrow, Mr Dew.

1272
01:06:45,001 --> 01:06:47,544
I wouldn't waste any time, Doctor.

1273
01:06:47,545 --> 01:06:50,047
This could be a very
serious matter for you.

1274
01:06:50,048 --> 01:06:54,009
But surely there's
no implication that...

1275
01:06:54,010 --> 01:06:57,262
I mean, my wife made her
intentions very plain to me.

1276
01:06:57,263 --> 01:07:01,225
Maybe so. But a complaint
has been made to the police.

1277
01:07:01,226 --> 01:07:04,520
So we've obviously got to trace
the lady to complete our inquiry.

1278
01:07:04,521 --> 01:07:07,022
But you must admit that I'm not
responsible for my wife's movements.

1279
01:07:07,023 --> 01:07:09,733
In the normal way, of course not.

1280
01:07:10,485 --> 01:07:13,278
But look at the facts here,
as we know them.

1281
01:07:13,279 --> 01:07:16,406
You admit yourself that you're
not on normal terms with her.

1282
01:07:18,034 --> 01:07:19,660
She has many friends,

1283
01:07:19,661 --> 01:07:22,037
but she disappears without
contacting any of them.

1284
01:07:22,038 --> 01:07:24,498
Instead of telling the truth
about her departure,

1285
01:07:24,499 --> 01:07:26,542
you invent a cock-and-bull story

1286
01:07:26,543 --> 01:07:29,419
about a mysterious death abroad.

1287
01:07:29,420 --> 01:07:32,881
At the same time,
you move another lady into the house

1288
01:07:32,882 --> 01:07:36,426
and deck her in your
wife's jewels and clothes.

1289
01:07:36,427 --> 01:07:39,346
As I bought them, I rather
fancied they belonged to me.

1290
01:07:39,347 --> 01:07:41,139
Possibly, I'm just pointing out

1291
01:07:41,140 --> 01:07:42,933
how the matter might appear.

1292
01:07:43,017 --> 01:07:44,601
Then you suspect me of something.

1293
01:07:44,602 --> 01:07:46,562
I didn't say that.

1294
01:07:46,563 --> 01:07:49,481
I’m just pointing out that with
these elements in the case,

1295
01:07:49,482 --> 01:07:53,110
we can't be satisfied until
we discover where your wife is.

1296
01:07:53,111 --> 01:07:54,861
I understand, Inspector.

1297
01:07:54,862 --> 01:07:56,697
I'll see the advertisement
goes in tomorrow.

1298
01:07:56,698 --> 01:07:59,408
I think that would be
the wise thing, sir.

1299
01:08:00,076 --> 01:08:01,660
Goodnight.

1300
01:08:08,334 --> 01:08:09,710
Goodnight, sir.

1301
01:08:09,711 --> 01:08:12,170
- Goodnight.
- Goodnight.

1302
01:08:13,506 --> 01:08:15,591
(CARRIAGE RATTLES ON STREET)

1303
01:08:21,014 --> 01:08:23,015
You don't really suspect
anything, do you, Guv?

1304
01:08:23,016 --> 01:08:24,474
Nah.

1305
01:08:24,475 --> 01:08:26,393
Why put the frighteners on him then?

1306
01:08:26,394 --> 01:08:28,979
What do you expect me to do,
give him a medal?

1307
01:08:28,980 --> 01:08:30,772
At best,
he's behaved like a damned fool,

1308
01:08:30,773 --> 01:08:32,816
involved us in a lot
of routine work...

1309
01:08:33,818 --> 01:08:35,611
..which won't lead anywhere.

1310
01:08:35,612 --> 01:08:39,197
That Le Neve is not a bad
little filly, though. I wonder.

1311
01:08:39,198 --> 01:08:41,450
Can you see a rabbit like that
polishing off his wife,

1312
01:08:41,451 --> 01:08:43,702
or anybody else, for that matter.

1313
01:08:43,703 --> 01:08:45,579
Sarge, you've seen him all day.

1314
01:08:45,580 --> 01:08:48,040
Nobody could be that calm
if he really had anything to hide.

1315
01:08:48,041 --> 01:08:51,043
Here, we didn't get his signature
on the carbon copy.

1316
01:08:51,044 --> 01:08:54,129
I'll nip round and get it on Monday.

1317
01:08:54,130 --> 01:08:57,132
I've had enough of those
codfish eyes for one day.

1318
01:08:57,133 --> 01:08:59,009
We're definitely going to drop it,
then?

1319
01:08:59,093 --> 01:09:01,511
When you've tidied up the paperwork,

1320
01:09:01,512 --> 01:09:04,514
we're going to file Dr Crippen
and forget him.

1321
01:09:04,515 --> 01:09:06,516
Where do you reckon the wife is,
then?

1322
01:09:07,935 --> 01:09:09,770
You saw the picture, didn't you?

1323
01:09:11,147 --> 01:09:13,148
A healthy-looking cow,
if ever I saw one.

1324
01:09:14,275 --> 01:09:18,153
Oh, she's off with some young buck
from the theatre, if you ask me.

1325
01:09:19,697 --> 01:09:21,156
Frankly, I don't blame her.

1326
01:09:22,367 --> 01:09:23,992
Crippen doesn't look as if he ever

1327
01:09:23,993 --> 01:09:25,744
had an emotion in his life.

1328
01:09:33,711 --> 01:09:36,505
(SHOVEL SCRAPES IN DISTANCE)

1329
01:10:17,004 --> 01:10:19,840
(SHOVEL SCRAPES)

1330
01:10:35,231 --> 01:10:37,733
- (SHE GASPS)
- Hawley, you frightened me.

1331
01:10:37,734 --> 01:10:39,443
What are you doing down here?

1332
01:10:39,444 --> 01:10:41,528
I’m just getting some coal
for the parlour.

1333
01:10:42,655 --> 01:10:44,740
I don't want you to do that.

1334
01:10:44,741 --> 01:10:45,907
Well, I just thought...

1335
01:10:45,908 --> 01:10:48,368
You know I don't like
you doing heavy work.

1336
01:10:48,369 --> 01:10:51,538
Besides, the dust ruins your hands.

1337
01:10:51,539 --> 01:10:53,665
The way you treat me,
you'd think I was too precious

1338
01:10:53,666 --> 01:10:55,167
to do any kind of work.

1339
01:10:55,168 --> 01:10:56,334
You are to me.

1340
01:10:57,795 --> 01:11:00,255
Here, you go on upstairs.

1341
01:11:00,256 --> 01:11:02,340
I'll bring the bucket.

1342
01:11:02,341 --> 01:11:06,136
All right, darling, but there's no
need to treat me like a China doll.

1343
01:11:06,137 --> 01:11:07,596
I like to.

1344
01:11:07,597 --> 01:11:10,432
(GENTLE MUSIC)

1345
01:11:22,528 --> 01:11:25,614
(TENSE MUSIC)

1346
01:11:52,391 --> 01:11:56,144
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC)

1347
01:12:01,484 --> 01:12:04,319
(GENTLE MUSIC)

1348
01:12:35,226 --> 01:12:37,978
(OMINOUS MUSIC)

1349
01:13:09,135 --> 01:13:12,387
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC)

1350
01:13:13,639 --> 01:13:16,057
(DOOR OPENS)

1351
01:13:16,058 --> 01:13:16,933
Who is it?

1352
01:13:16,934 --> 01:13:19,019
Darling.

1353
01:13:19,020 --> 01:13:20,145
What's the matter?

1354
01:13:23,482 --> 01:13:26,318
I just couldn't sleep.

1355
01:13:27,737 --> 01:13:30,780
No, it's more than that.

1356
01:13:33,326 --> 01:13:35,785
It's something to do with
the police, isn't it?

1357
01:13:37,121 --> 01:13:39,539
Yes, they think
I've done some harm to Belle.

1358
01:13:40,917 --> 01:13:42,792
But that’s ridiculous.

1359
01:13:42,793 --> 01:13:45,045
She's with that man, Martin.

1360
01:13:45,046 --> 01:13:47,422
I know, but how can I prove it?

1361
01:13:47,423 --> 01:13:48,882
She'll see your advertisement.

1362
01:13:48,883 --> 01:13:50,675
You don't know Belle.

1363
01:13:50,676 --> 01:13:52,135
She hates me.

1364
01:13:52,136 --> 01:13:53,845
She'll realise what it means,

1365
01:13:53,846 --> 01:13:56,932
and deliberately not answer it
just to get me into trouble.

1366
01:13:58,142 --> 01:14:01,519
We'll find her. We’ll get someone
in America to go and see her.

1367
01:14:01,520 --> 01:14:02,771
That'd convince the police.

1368
01:14:02,772 --> 01:14:05,774
No, it's no use. By that time,
they will have arrested me.

1369
01:14:05,775 --> 01:14:07,233
They can't arrest you for nothing.

1370
01:14:07,234 --> 01:14:09,611
They can hold me
while they look for Belle.

1371
01:14:10,947 --> 01:14:12,072
Even if they do,

1372
01:14:12,073 --> 01:14:14,074
it can only be fora short time.

1373
01:14:14,075 --> 01:14:16,034
Until they discover the truth.

1374
01:14:17,286 --> 01:14:18,620
I'm a doctor.

1375
01:14:18,621 --> 01:14:20,455
The scandal would ruin me.

1376
01:14:20,456 --> 01:14:23,166
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

1377
01:14:23,167 --> 01:14:25,460
You're sure there's
nothing else worrying you?

1378
01:14:25,461 --> 01:14:27,212
You don't know what lengths
she'll go to,

1379
01:14:27,213 --> 01:14:29,464
to hurt me and to get her own back.

1380
01:14:29,465 --> 01:14:31,925
Why, she'd even disappear in America

1381
01:14:31,926 --> 01:14:34,678
if she thought she could
get me into worse trouble.

1382
01:14:34,679 --> 01:14:37,472
(GENTLE MUSIC)

1383
01:14:43,312 --> 01:14:45,021
What do you want to do, Hawley?

1384
01:14:47,024 --> 01:14:48,483
I want to leave here.

1385
01:14:51,862 --> 01:14:53,279
I want to take you with me.

1386
01:14:55,866 --> 01:14:57,826
I'd go anywhere with you.

1387
01:14:59,203 --> 01:15:00,912
We'll go tomorrow.

1388
01:15:00,913 --> 01:15:02,205
Where to?

1389
01:15:02,206 --> 01:15:04,374
The continent first,
and then the States.

1390
01:15:05,584 --> 01:15:07,836
Oh, that's marvellous.
First thing in the morning,

1391
01:15:07,837 --> 01:15:09,629
I’ll go and say goodbye
to Mrs Jackson.

1392
01:15:09,630 --> 01:15:11,339
No, if we're going to go,

1393
01:15:11,340 --> 01:15:13,758
let's just walk out
and sever all ties.

1394
01:15:15,428 --> 01:15:18,304
All right, if you think so.

1395
01:15:19,432 --> 01:15:22,350
I know you think I’m overdoing it,
but I don't trust these police.

1396
01:15:22,351 --> 01:15:24,060
The sooner we're on our way

1397
01:15:24,061 --> 01:15:26,521
and with the least fuss, the better.

1398
01:15:26,522 --> 01:15:28,898
What a lucky thing I bought
that grey dress last week.

1399
01:15:28,899 --> 01:15:30,191
I can travel in that,

1400
01:15:30,192 --> 01:15:31,901
and I think
I’ll wear that flame hat.

1401
01:15:31,902 --> 01:15:33,445
If we’re going to go like this,

1402
01:15:33,446 --> 01:15:35,280
we don't want to leave
any trails behind us.

1403
01:15:35,281 --> 01:15:39,659
A middle-aged man
and a young girl...

1404
01:15:41,203 --> 01:15:43,246
..will be signposted
wherever they go.

1405
01:15:44,373 --> 01:15:45,707
You want to travel separately?

1406
01:15:45,708 --> 01:15:49,085
No, but I think we should
disguise ourselves,

1407
01:15:49,086 --> 01:15:51,337
until we're clear away from England.

1408
01:15:51,338 --> 01:15:55,050
That way,
even if the police, or Belle,

1409
01:15:55,051 --> 01:15:57,761
do try to find us,
they won't be able to.

1410
01:16:00,848 --> 01:16:03,433
(GENTLE MUSIC)

1411
01:16:04,727 --> 01:16:07,395
(BRIGHT MUSIC)

1412
01:16:40,096 --> 01:16:42,388
What a wonderful father
Mr Robinson is.

1413
01:16:42,389 --> 01:16:44,599
He never leaves his son's side.

1414
01:16:44,600 --> 01:16:47,352
The boy seems to look
a bit effeminate to me.

1415
01:17:09,333 --> 01:17:11,209
Let's sit over there, Tom.

1416
01:17:16,841 --> 01:17:18,216
What can I get you, sir?

1417
01:17:19,426 --> 01:17:21,886
Well, thank you,
my son will have a glass of milk,

1418
01:17:21,887 --> 01:17:23,304
and I'll take a sherry.

1419
01:17:23,305 --> 01:17:24,639
Very good, sir.

1420
01:17:27,059 --> 01:17:29,853
Why can't I have something
more interesting than milk?

1421
01:17:29,854 --> 01:17:32,188
Because you're only a little boy.

1422
01:17:37,528 --> 01:17:39,028
I always
forget to put a handkerchief

1423
01:17:39,029 --> 01:17:40,238
in these wretched pockets.

1424
01:17:40,239 --> 01:17:41,489
Here, here.

1425
01:17:41,490 --> 01:17:43,032
- Have mine.
- No, thank you, darling.

1426
01:17:43,033 --> 01:17:44,534
I want to go back
to the cabin anyway.

1427
01:17:44,535 --> 01:17:46,286
- Don't be long.
-Yeah.

1428
01:17:53,669 --> 01:17:55,211
Hello, Mr Robinson.

1429
01:17:58,299 --> 01:17:59,716
Mr Robinson.

1430
01:18:01,260 --> 01:18:03,595
Oh, sorry, Captain,
I didn't hear you.

1431
01:18:04,889 --> 01:18:07,182
I hope you're enjoying your trip.

1432
01:18:07,183 --> 01:18:09,225
Oh, yes, thank you, very much.

1433
01:18:09,226 --> 01:18:11,477
I must congratulate you on the ship.

1434
01:18:11,478 --> 01:18:13,146
She's most comfortable.

1435
01:18:14,315 --> 01:18:16,316
Do you mind if I join you?

1436
01:18:16,317 --> 01:18:17,317
No, please.

1437
01:18:17,318 --> 01:18:19,444
Please.

1438
01:18:22,698 --> 01:18:24,407
May I offer you some refreshment?

1439
01:18:24,408 --> 01:18:25,700
No, thank you very much.

1440
01:18:25,701 --> 01:18:27,577
I was just wondering
whether you and your son

1441
01:18:27,578 --> 01:18:30,246
would join my table again
for dinner tonight?

1442
01:18:30,247 --> 01:18:32,290
That's most cordial of you.

1443
01:18:32,291 --> 01:18:34,125
A good-looking boy, your son.

1444
01:18:34,126 --> 01:18:35,501
We're all quite taken with him.

1445
01:18:35,502 --> 01:18:37,212
Yes, he's always very popular.

1446
01:18:37,213 --> 01:18:39,714
Enjoying himself at sea,
do you think?

1447
01:18:39,715 --> 01:18:41,925
Oh, yes, indeed.

1448
01:18:42,009 --> 01:18:44,177
Now that it's calm.

1449
01:18:44,178 --> 01:18:47,639
He wasn't too happy the first
few days out from An twerp,

1450
01:18:47,640 --> 01:18:49,140
but then, neither was I.

1451
01:18:49,141 --> 01:18:52,727
He seems to have got his sea legs
now, all right.

1452
01:18:52,728 --> 01:18:54,562
We ought to recruit him
for the line.

1453
01:18:54,563 --> 01:18:56,189
The lady passengers always like
having

1454
01:18:56,190 --> 01:18:57,941
a handsome young cadet
about the place.

1455
01:18:57,942 --> 01:18:59,776
Yes, I expect they do.

1456
01:18:59,777 --> 01:19:02,320
As a matter of fact, I've got
a son just about his age,

1457
01:19:02,321 --> 01:19:04,864
that I've been trying to press-gang
aboard, but he won't have it.

1458
01:19:04,949 --> 01:19:07,325
He's absolutely crazy
about motor cars

1459
01:19:07,326 --> 01:19:09,035
and won't hear of anything else.

1460
01:19:09,870 --> 01:19:12,372
Has your boy made up his mind
what he wants to be yet?

1461
01:19:13,916 --> 01:19:15,375
No, not exactly,

1462
01:19:15,376 --> 01:19:18,753
but there's still plenty of time.

1463
01:19:18,754 --> 01:19:21,381
I expect you'll want to take him
into the family business,

1464
01:19:21,382 --> 01:19:22,966
like most fathers.

1465
01:19:22,967 --> 01:19:24,467
Engineering, isn't it?

1466
01:19:24,468 --> 01:19:27,262
Yes, it's in that line, anyway.

1467
01:19:27,263 --> 01:19:31,057
Oh, Tom, the Captain here has
been telling me about his son.

1468
01:19:32,142 --> 01:19:34,269
Are you fond of games, young Tom?

1469
01:19:34,270 --> 01:19:36,688
I quite enjoy them.

1470
01:19:36,689 --> 01:19:38,398
Some of the young gentlemen aboard

1471
01:19:38,399 --> 01:19:41,192
make up a game of
deck-hockey before breakfast.

1472
01:19:41,193 --> 01:19:42,777
Just shorts and a singlet.

1473
01:19:42,778 --> 01:19:44,070
Why don't you join them?

1474
01:19:45,155 --> 01:19:48,157
Well, actually, Tom hasn't been
feeling too well lately.

1475
01:19:48,158 --> 01:19:50,868
That's really why
I brought him on this trip.

1476
01:19:50,869 --> 01:19:52,453
I'm sorry to hear that.

1477
01:19:52,454 --> 01:19:54,205
I thought he looked a bit pale.

1478
01:19:55,416 --> 01:19:58,167
Well, see you this evening then.

1479
01:19:58,168 --> 01:19:59,585
Yes, thank you.

1480
01:19:59,586 --> 01:20:01,254
We're most obliged to you.

1481
01:20:08,429 --> 01:20:10,263
Do we really have to eat with him?

1482
01:20:11,307 --> 01:20:13,308
Yes, I'm afraid so.

1483
01:20:13,309 --> 01:20:14,934
It's quite an honour.

1484
01:20:14,935 --> 01:20:16,728
I wish we needn't.

1485
01:20:16,729 --> 01:20:18,146
I know.

1486
01:20:18,147 --> 01:20:21,733
But we... We've got to keep up
some appearances.

1487
01:20:23,610 --> 01:20:26,487
(MACHINE BEEPS)

1488
01:20:29,033 --> 01:20:31,117
Andrews, make this to London office.

1489
01:20:31,118 --> 01:20:32,201
Yes, sir.

1490
01:20:32,202 --> 01:20:34,078
"Further to my message,

1491
01:20:34,079 --> 01:20:36,164
"convinced beyond doubt

1492
01:20:36,165 --> 01:20:38,416
"Crippen and Le Neve
aboard travelling,

1493
01:20:38,417 --> 01:20:40,752
"disguised as father and son, stop.

1494
01:20:40,753 --> 01:20:44,422
"Believe them quite unaware
of my suspicions, stop.

1495
01:20:45,632 --> 01:20:48,301
"Will keep them under
constant surveillance, stop.

1496
01:20:49,470 --> 01:20:51,304
"Please advise."

1497
01:20:51,305 --> 01:20:52,972
Are you sure it's him, sir?

1498
01:20:52,973 --> 01:20:54,766
- Convinced.
- Well, how did you get on to them?

1499
01:20:54,767 --> 01:20:57,185
The English papers I saw in Antwerp

1500
01:20:57,186 --> 01:20:59,854
had their photographs spread
all over the front pages.

1501
01:20:59,855 --> 01:21:01,356
Poor devils.

1502
01:21:01,357 --> 01:21:03,524
Thinking they've got away with it.

1503
01:21:03,525 --> 01:21:05,526
I don't know how they hoped
to get away with it

1504
01:21:05,527 --> 01:21:07,195
disguised as father and son.

1505
01:21:08,322 --> 01:21:11,366
She's got a very feminine
figure fora boy of 16,

1506
01:21:11,367 --> 01:21:13,951
and he can't keep his hands off her,
even in public.

1507
01:21:13,952 --> 01:21:17,497
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

1508
01:21:34,181 --> 01:21:35,890
Hawley, we must be more careful.

1509
01:21:35,891 --> 01:21:37,475
We'll be seen.

1510
01:21:37,476 --> 01:21:39,268
I feel so happy.

1511
01:21:39,269 --> 01:21:40,728
I don't really care.

1512
01:21:43,065 --> 01:21:45,942
Are you pleased to be going home,
darling?

1513
01:21:45,943 --> 01:21:47,402
Yes, of course, but...

1514
01:21:48,487 --> 01:21:50,988
..I've been away from America
for so long that

1515
01:21:50,989 --> 01:21:53,616
I'm beginning to feel
like an English gentleman.

1516
01:21:53,617 --> 01:21:56,536
You could never be that,
not the way you behave.

1517
01:22:00,541 --> 01:22:05,545
Hawley, you don't think
Belle could ever find us?

1518
01:22:06,839 --> 01:22:09,424
I mean, if she ever tired
of that Martin man.

1519
01:22:10,968 --> 01:22:13,386
America is a very big place,
my darling.

1520
01:22:14,596 --> 01:22:18,933
We'll find somewhere
and start a new life together.

1521
01:22:18,934 --> 01:22:21,686
(GENTLE MUSIC)

1522
01:22:24,231 --> 01:22:27,358
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

1523
01:22:31,155 --> 01:22:32,613
Sir.

1524
01:22:32,614 --> 01:22:33,948
Thank you.

1525
01:22:33,949 --> 01:22:37,243
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC)

1526
01:22:43,167 --> 01:22:46,085
A Scotland Yard inspector will be
coming aboard with the pilot.

1527
01:22:46,086 --> 01:22:48,671
You'll meet him
and take him to Robinson's cabin,

1528
01:22:48,672 --> 01:22:50,339
and for heaven's sake be discreet.

1529
01:22:50,340 --> 01:22:52,091
Aye-aye, sir.

1530
01:22:52,092 --> 01:22:55,011
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

1531
01:22:56,972 --> 01:23:00,057
(TENDER MUSIC)

1532
01:23:13,989 --> 01:23:15,823
Hawley, I love you.

1533
01:23:18,368 --> 01:23:19,994
I love you so much.

1534
01:23:22,122 --> 01:23:23,539
I love you.

1535
01:23:40,516 --> 01:23:41,766
Hawley.

1536
01:23:44,770 --> 01:23:46,020
I love you.

1537
01:23:50,108 --> 01:23:51,859
I love you.

1538
01:23:53,028 --> 01:23:55,738
(TENDER MUSIC)

1539
01:24:05,082 --> 01:24:08,042
(SEABIRDS CRY)

1540
01:24:14,341 --> 01:24:17,927
(WATER LAPS FAINTLY)

1541
01:24:17,928 --> 01:24:19,512
The engines have stopped.

1542
01:24:21,974 --> 01:24:23,099
Hmm?

1543
01:24:27,896 --> 01:24:29,605
Oh.

1544
01:24:29,606 --> 01:24:31,774
There's a cutter coming alongside.

1545
01:24:33,235 --> 01:24:34,986
It must be the Canadian pilot.

1546
01:24:38,323 --> 01:24:40,283
Only a few more hours now.

1547
01:24:40,284 --> 01:24:42,243
Where are we going to go
after we land?

1548
01:24:42,244 --> 01:24:45,079
I thought, maybe out west somewhere,

1549
01:24:45,080 --> 01:24:47,081
Los Angeles or San Francisco.

1550
01:24:48,250 --> 01:24:51,752
Six months ago, I’d made up mind
there was no future for us at all.

1551
01:24:51,753 --> 01:24:53,254
I thought the best
I could hope for

1552
01:24:53,255 --> 01:24:56,591
was seeing you once a week
in that dreadful hotel.

1553
01:24:56,592 --> 01:24:57,842
I thought you liked it.

1554
01:24:57,843 --> 01:24:59,594
Ugh, it made me vomit.

1555
01:24:59,595 --> 01:25:03,472
All those people looking at us
and knowing and sneering.

1556
01:25:03,473 --> 01:25:05,433
My poor darling.

1557
01:25:05,434 --> 01:25:07,768
It won’t be long now anyway.

1558
01:25:07,769 --> 01:25:11,856
(BELL RINGS IN DISTANCE)

1559
01:25:17,112 --> 01:25:20,448
I wonder how long it's gonna take
for my hair to grow.

1560
01:25:20,449 --> 01:25:22,158
A few weeks, I expect.

1561
01:25:24,411 --> 01:25:25,494
Thank you.

1562
01:25:26,913 --> 01:25:28,456
For what?

1563
01:25:28,457 --> 01:25:29,790
For being Ethel.

1564
01:25:30,917 --> 01:25:34,670
Forgiving me the only
real happiness I've ever had.

1565
01:25:34,671 --> 01:25:36,839
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

1566
01:25:44,931 --> 01:25:45,931
Come in.

1567
01:25:47,643 --> 01:25:50,061
Excuse me, sir. Someone would
like to have a word with you.

1568
01:25:57,986 --> 01:26:00,446
I think you know who I am, Doctor.

1569
01:26:06,161 --> 01:26:08,329
You come along with me now, sir.

1570
01:26:12,793 --> 01:26:14,710
Whatever happens now, darling,

1571
01:26:14,711 --> 01:26:17,963
always remember that
I loved you with all my soul.

1572
01:26:17,964 --> 01:26:21,175
All right, sir, come along.

1573
01:26:21,176 --> 01:26:24,345
(GENTLE MUSIC)

1574
01:26:26,973 --> 01:26:28,015
Hawley.

1575
01:26:35,899 --> 01:26:37,775
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

1576
01:26:37,776 --> 01:26:39,485
You'd better come along with me.

1577
01:26:49,204 --> 01:26:52,039
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

1578
01:27:17,941 --> 01:27:19,567
Prisoners up.

1579
01:27:32,873 --> 01:27:35,583
(TENSE MUSIC)

1580
01:27:44,050 --> 01:27:47,386
Gentlemen, have you
agreed upon your verdict?

1581
01:27:47,387 --> 01:27:48,471
We have.

1582
01:27:48,472 --> 01:27:50,097
Do you find the prisoner, Crippen,

1583
01:27:50,098 --> 01:27:53,142
guilty or not guilty
of wilful murder?

1584
01:27:54,519 --> 01:27:56,771
We find the prisoner guilty.

1585
01:27:56,772 --> 01:27:59,899
(CROWD MUTTERS)

1586
01:27:59,900 --> 01:28:01,650
You find the prisoner guilty,

1587
01:28:01,651 --> 01:28:03,277
and that is the verdict of you all?

1588
01:28:03,278 --> 01:28:04,320
It is.

1589
01:28:05,530 --> 01:28:09,200
Do you find the prisoner,
Le Neve, guilty or not guilty

1590
01:28:09,201 --> 01:28:11,619
of being an accessory
after the fact in murder?

1591
01:28:11,620 --> 01:28:13,078
Not guilty.

1592
01:28:14,664 --> 01:28:16,582
You find the prisoner not guilty,

1593
01:28:16,583 --> 01:28:18,000
and that is the verdict of you all?

1594
01:28:18,001 --> 01:28:18,793
It is.

1595
01:28:18,794 --> 01:28:22,713
Ethel Le Neve, you are discharged.

1596
01:28:30,555 --> 01:28:32,848
No! They're all lying!

1597
01:28:32,849 --> 01:28:35,392
She's alive, I tell you!
She's alive!

1598
01:28:35,393 --> 01:28:38,312
He didn't do it. He didn't do it!

1599
01:28:38,313 --> 01:28:40,606
She's alive, I tell you!
She's alive!

1600
01:28:40,607 --> 01:28:43,609
No, look, they're lying!
They're lying! He didn't do it!

1601
01:28:43,610 --> 01:28:46,612
He didn't do it! No!

1602
01:28:46,613 --> 01:28:47,947
Prisoner at the bar...

1603
01:28:47,948 --> 01:28:49,114
(ETHEL SOBS)

1604
01:28:49,115 --> 01:28:52,326
..you stand convicted of murder.

1605
01:28:52,327 --> 01:28:54,119
Have you anything to say
why the Court

1606
01:28:54,204 --> 01:28:57,414
should not give you judgement
of death according to law?

1607
01:29:00,919 --> 01:29:05,047
Only, that I am innocent of murder.

1608
01:29:05,048 --> 01:29:08,717
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC)

1609
01:29:14,558 --> 01:29:16,767
Hawley Harvey Crippen,

1610
01:29:16,768 --> 01:29:18,561
you have been convicted on evidence

1611
01:29:18,562 --> 01:29:21,564
of a ghastly and wicked crime.

1612
01:29:21,565 --> 01:29:25,192
I have now to pass upon you
the sentence of the Court,

1613
01:29:25,193 --> 01:29:28,362
which is that you shall be
taken to a lawful prison,

1614
01:29:28,363 --> 01:29:30,114
and from thence
to a place of execution,

1615
01:29:30,115 --> 01:29:33,868
and there be hanged by the neck
until you are dead.

1616
01:29:35,620 --> 01:29:37,955
(FOREBODING MUSIC)

1617
01:29:41,668 --> 01:29:44,628
(TENSE MUSIC)

1618
01:29:52,012 --> 01:29:54,388
It's 25 past seven, Doctor.

1619
01:29:55,891 --> 01:29:58,142
Yes, thank you, Mr Harding.

1620
01:30:00,061 --> 01:30:02,104
Is there anything I can get you,
sir?

1621
01:30:03,773 --> 01:30:05,691
I’d like to wash, I think.

1622
01:30:13,408 --> 01:30:15,284
Mrs Crippen always used to say that,

1623
01:30:15,285 --> 01:30:18,704
"If cleanliness
was next to godliness,

1624
01:30:18,705 --> 01:30:20,831
"I'd die an archbishop."

1625
01:30:22,792 --> 01:30:24,335
She was wrong, wasn't she?

1626
01:30:51,154 --> 01:30:53,447
ls there anything else you'd like,
sir?

1627
01:30:54,991 --> 01:30:56,992
No, I don't think so.

1628
01:30:56,993 --> 01:30:59,036
Thank you, Mr Harding.

1629
01:30:59,037 --> 01:31:03,666
Except, in case I don't get a chance
to say this later, I...

1630
01:31:04,751 --> 01:31:08,170
I'm very grateful to you
and your colleagues

1631
01:31:08,171 --> 01:31:11,173
for your kindness and courtesy
during these past weeks.

1632
01:31:11,174 --> 01:31:14,176
It can't have been
a very pleasant assignment.

1633
01:31:16,680 --> 01:31:19,974
I’m really terribly sorry, Doctor.

1634
01:31:21,977 --> 01:31:24,603
What none of us here
can understand...

1635
01:31:24,604 --> 01:31:26,480
(DOOR CREAKS OPEN)

1636
01:31:28,817 --> 01:31:30,818
All right, Harding,
you may wait outside.

1637
01:31:32,320 --> 01:31:33,988
No, it's all right.

1638
01:31:33,989 --> 01:31:35,489
Well, very good, sir.

1639
01:31:38,368 --> 01:31:41,120
- (DOOR THUDS)
- Miss Le Neve sent you this telegram.

1640
01:31:41,121 --> 01:31:43,998
I’m sorry that regulations
forced me to open it.

1641
01:31:45,291 --> 01:31:46,500
Thank you.

1642
01:31:58,596 --> 01:32:00,097
I'm very much obliged to you

1643
01:32:00,098 --> 01:32:02,808
for letting me read it, Governor.

1644
01:32:02,809 --> 01:32:04,018
ls there anything
that I can do for you?

1645
01:32:04,019 --> 01:32:06,729
Yes.

1646
01:32:06,730 --> 01:32:09,690
I would like her
letters and photographs

1647
01:32:09,691 --> 01:32:12,276
buried with me,
if that's possible.

1648
01:32:12,277 --> 01:32:14,028
I’ll see to that myself.

1649
01:32:15,196 --> 01:32:17,573
If only I could be sure
that they'll give her a chance.

1650
01:32:17,574 --> 01:32:19,533
I could arrange to visit her myself

1651
01:32:19,534 --> 01:32:22,036
from time to time,
if that would be a help.

1652
01:32:22,037 --> 01:32:24,163
Oh, yes, please.

1653
01:32:24,164 --> 01:32:26,373
If only you could persuade her
that she must make

1654
01:32:26,374 --> 01:32:27,875
an entirely new life for herself,

1655
01:32:27,876 --> 01:32:29,918
take a different name,

1656
01:32:29,919 --> 01:32:33,797
and never, never let anybody
know who she really is.

1657
01:32:33,798 --> 01:32:34,923
Of course.

1658
01:32:34,924 --> 01:32:36,842
You'll like her, Governor.

1659
01:32:36,926 --> 01:32:41,221
She's simple and real,
and direct and honest.

1660
01:32:41,222 --> 01:32:43,098
The papers try to make her out

1661
01:32:43,099 --> 01:32:44,558
to be some sort of scar let woman,

1662
01:32:44,559 --> 01:32:47,019
but the jury weren't fooled.

1663
01:32:47,020 --> 01:32:49,563
They could tell what she was
just by looking at her.

1664
01:32:51,441 --> 01:32:53,275
You know, Crippen,
I've never met anyone

1665
01:32:53,276 --> 01:32:56,195
who struck me as being less likely
to commit murder than yourself,

1666
01:32:56,196 --> 01:32:57,654
whatever the pressures.

1667
01:32:58,782 --> 01:33:00,616
But I didn't murder her.

1668
01:33:00,617 --> 01:33:02,910
Then you still protest
your innocence?

1669
01:33:02,911 --> 01:33:05,913
I killed her, all right,
but it was an accident.

1670
01:33:05,914 --> 01:33:08,624
Why in heaven's name
didn't you say so at the trial,

1671
01:33:08,625 --> 01:33:09,958
or at the appeal?

1672
01:33:10,794 --> 01:33:13,462
Is what I say to you
treated as confidential?

1673
01:33:13,463 --> 01:33:15,798
Absolutely, I give you my word.

1674
01:33:16,883 --> 01:33:19,760
Well, I'd like somebody
to know the truth.

1675
01:33:21,596 --> 01:33:22,763
You see...

1676
01:33:24,516 --> 01:33:27,768
..Belle and I
had been growing apart,

1677
01:33:27,769 --> 01:33:29,645
long before I met Ethel.

1678
01:33:31,147 --> 01:33:34,525
She wasn't a bad woman, really,
but coarse and dirty.

1679
01:33:34,526 --> 01:33:37,486
Love, to her,
was a matter of appetite,

1680
01:33:37,487 --> 01:33:39,822
whereas to me...

1681
01:33:41,032 --> 01:33:42,866
Well, I found what I wanted
in Ethel.

1682
01:33:42,867 --> 01:33:46,370
So I planned to give Belle
regular sedatives

1683
01:33:46,371 --> 01:33:47,538
to calm her down.

1684
01:33:47,539 --> 01:33:50,082
I remember thinking
the night she died...

1685
01:33:51,417 --> 01:33:54,086
We'd had
a particularly dreadful quarrel.

1686
01:33:54,087 --> 01:33:55,462
She was drunk.

1687
01:33:56,840 --> 01:33:58,841
I remember thinking then

1688
01:33:58,842 --> 01:34:01,677
that I would've liked to kill her.

1689
01:34:03,638 --> 01:34:06,348
So I’m not entirely innocent.

1690
01:34:07,642 --> 01:34:09,184
The thought was there.

1691
01:34:11,187 --> 01:34:14,481
They said they found halfa grain
of hyoscine in the body.

1692
01:34:16,234 --> 01:34:17,734
I'm still puzzling over that.

1693
01:34:18,903 --> 01:34:22,281
I could've sworn I didn't give her
more than the regular sedative dose.

1694
01:34:23,658 --> 01:34:25,159
Anyway, she died...

1695
01:34:26,494 --> 01:34:27,578
..and then I panicked.

1696
01:34:27,579 --> 01:34:29,872
I realised there'd be an inquest,

1697
01:34:29,873 --> 01:34:31,915
and I didn't think they'd believe me

1698
01:34:31,916 --> 01:34:33,792
because of my relationship
with Ethel.

1699
01:34:34,961 --> 01:34:38,672
So I made up that story about
Belle going off with another man.

1700
01:34:38,673 --> 01:34:42,301
But when they arrested you,
why didn't you tell the truth then?

1701
01:34:42,302 --> 01:34:45,262
Well, by that time
there was such a hullabaloo.

1702
01:34:46,389 --> 01:34:47,681
I was a monster.

1703
01:34:49,017 --> 01:34:52,144
Worse than Jack the Ripper,
if you could believe the newspaper.

1704
01:34:53,229 --> 01:34:54,938
I didn't think they'd acquit me
anyway,

1705
01:34:54,939 --> 01:34:59,193
not after what I'd done to...
to hide the remains.

1706
01:35:00,361 --> 01:35:02,779
So, as my life was lost...

1707
01:35:03,823 --> 01:35:06,867
..the most important thing
was to keep alive the thing

1708
01:35:06,868 --> 01:35:10,162
I treasured more than
anything else in the world,

1709
01:35:10,163 --> 01:35:13,957
Ethel's love and her belief in me.

1710
01:35:15,710 --> 01:35:20,214
She still doesn't think I had
anything to do with that body.

1711
01:35:21,549 --> 01:35:25,260
She thinks Belle is alive somewhere,
laughing.

1712
01:35:27,096 --> 01:35:31,141
She's a very simple, lovely girl.

1713
01:35:32,727 --> 01:35:35,729
I couldn't have borne it
if she turned against me, too.

1714
01:35:38,024 --> 01:35:39,316
I'll do everything I can

1715
01:35:39,317 --> 01:35:41,652
to see she gets the chance
of a new life.

1716
01:35:41,653 --> 01:35:43,946
You won't mention any of this
to her?

1717
01:35:43,947 --> 01:35:46,281
Nothing that you wouldn't
want her to hear.

1718
01:35:46,282 --> 01:35:48,742
(DOOR CREAKS OPEN)

1719
01:35:49,911 --> 01:35:52,079
It's ten minutes to eight, sir.

1720
01:35:53,373 --> 01:35:54,456
Goodbye then.

1721
01:35:55,375 --> 01:35:57,209
Goodbye, sir.

1722
01:36:10,098 --> 01:36:11,390
Doctor.

1723
01:36:14,018 --> 01:36:15,143
Sir.

1724
01:36:21,150 --> 01:36:22,276
It's time.

1725
01:36:28,658 --> 01:36:32,911
I was just thinking...
Mr Harding.

1726
01:36:34,872 --> 01:36:37,082
In a few minutes,
it'll all be over for me.

1727
01:36:38,793 --> 01:36:40,043
But for her...

1728
01:36:41,379 --> 01:36:43,630
..it'll go on
for the rest of her life.

1729
01:36:58,896 --> 01:37:02,190
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

1730
01:37:26,466 --> 01:37:29,051
(BELL TOLLS)

1731
01:37:35,141 --> 01:37:38,060
(BELL TOLLS)

1732
01:38:02,293 --> 01:38:05,253
(SOMBRE MUSIC)

